ath using BuildArgs to the native-image builder. Also, my Gradle task should ensure the stub is a dependency of nativeTestCompile.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Understanding initialization logic**\\n\\nI need to ensure that the site is called even if the initialization fails, but only if the library is loaded. In the static initializer, the order is crucial — newInstance happens first, followed by the initialize catch. The RXTXCommDriver.initialize can call a native method, which could throw an UnsatisfiedLinkError if the library isn't loaded yet. If there's no stub at build time, the class initialization might fail. I’m considering using a build argument like --initialize-at-build-time to address this while ensuring all call sites are tracked properly.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Implementing test support**\\n\\nI need to add a test support class that will statically initialize and call getPortIdentifiers. By doing this, I can ensure that the initialization happens at build time. This approach helps in avoiding issues related to dynamic initialization during runtime, making it easier to manage any dependencies and ensuring that everything is configured correctly before the actual tests run. It seems like a good step toward improving the overall robustness of my code.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering build adjustments**\\n\\nI need to edit the `build.gradle` file and run some tests. I’m wondering if I should also tweak the native stub output since just setting `LD_LIBRARY_PATH` on Test tasks might not be sufficient for the native-image runtime in `nativeTest`. It seems like the native Test task for the native executable might be of a different type than the standard Test task. I need to check if the plugin’s `nativeTest` behaves differently and how the native test executable is configured through binaries.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_xEeIMb8H9YaPqBLmiSrnADhw|fc_0e64ebe85c220c0a0169f27212d2f881a1bf32abea